  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Which are the best Hollywood movies of 2016?",
  "response": "2016 was a strong year for Hollywood, producing a mix of critically acclaimed films, box office hits, and award-winning movies. Here\u2019s a list of some of the best films from that year:\n\n### **Critical and Commercial Successes**\n1. **La La Land**  \n   - Directed by Damien Chazelle, this modern musical starring Emma Stone and Ryan Gosling was a massive hit, earning 14 Oscar nominations and winning 6, including Best Director.\n\n2. **Moonlight**  \n   - Directed by Barry Jenkins, this poignant coming-of-age drama won the Academy Award for Best Picture, along with two other Oscars.\n\n3. **Arrival**  \n   - Denis Villeneuve\u2019s sci-fi masterpiece, starring Amy Adams, was praised for its intellectual depth and emotional storytelling.\n\n4. **Manchester by the Sea**  \n   - Kenneth Lonergan\u2019s heartbreaking drama earned Casey Affleck an Oscar for Best Actor and featured a powerful performance by Michelle Williams.\n\n5. **Hacksaw Ridge**  \n   - Mel Gibson\u2019s war drama, based on the true story of Desmond Doss, was a critical and commercial success, earning multiple Oscar nominations.\n\n---\n\n### **Blockbusters and Fan Favorites**\n6. **Captain America: Civil War**  \n   - This Marvel Cinematic Universe installment was a massive hit, pitting Captain America against Iron Man in a thrilling superhero showdown.\n\n7. **Rogue One: A Star Wars Story**  \n   - A standalone Star Wars film that was praised for its gritty tone and connection to the original trilogy.\n\n8. **Deadpool**  \n   - Ryan Reynolds\u2019 irreverent take on the Marvel antihero broke box office records and became a cultural phenomenon.\n\n9. **Zootopia**  \n   - Disney\u2019s animated hit combined humor, heart, and a timely message about inclusivity.\n\n---\n\n### **Other Notable Films**\n10. **Hell or High Water**  \n    - A modern Western crime drama starring Chris Pine and Ben Foster, with Jeff Bridges delivering an Oscar-nominated performance.\n\n11. **The Jungle Book**  \n    - Jon Favreau\u2019s visually stunning live-action adaptation of the Disney classic was a critical and commercial success.\n\n12. **Sing Street**  \n    - John Carney\u2019s charming coming-of-age musical about a boy forming a band in 1980s Dublin.\n\n13. **Kubo and the Two Strings**  \n    - Laika\u2019s stop-motion animated adventure was praised for its creativity and storytelling.\n\n14. **The Nice Guys**  \n    - Shane Black\u2019s action-comedy starring Ryan Gosling and Russell Crowe was a sleeper hit with sharp writing and great chemistry.\n\n15. **Hidden Figures**  \n    - The inspiring true story of African-American women mathematicians at NASA, starring Taraji P. Henson, Octavia Spencer, and Janelle Mon\u00e1e.\n\n---\n\n### **Award Contenders**\n16. **Fences**  \n    - Denzel Washington\u2019s adaptation of the August Wilson play, starring himself and Viola Davis, earned critical acclaim and Oscars.\n\n17. **Lion**  \n    - Based on a true story, this emotional drama starring Dev Patel and Nicole Kidman was a multiple Oscar nominee.\n\n18. **Jackie**  \n    - Natalie Portman\u2019s portrayal of Jackie Kennedy in the aftermath of JFK\u2019s assassination earned her widespread acclaim.\n\n---\n\nThese films represent a diverse range of genres and styles, making 2016 a memorable year for cinema.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
